   "collection": "Tretyakov Gallery",
   "story": {
    "extract": "Composition VII is a 1913 abstract oil painting by Russian-born painter Wassily Kandinsky. It is in the collection of the Tretyakov Gallery, in Moscow. Art historians have concluded that the work is a combination of the themes of Resurrection, Judgment Day, the Flood and the Garden of Eden.",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_VII"
   },
   "facts": [
    {
     "text": "Kandinsky's preliminary study was his first abstract watercolor. Untitled (Study for Composition VII, Première abstraction) was painted in 1913, and is the first of Kandinsky's \"Compositions\" and \"Improvisations\" series that began to emerge during his Blue Rider Period.",
     "section": "Preliminary watercolor",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_VII#Preliminary_watercolor"
    },
    {
     "text": "The work demonstrates characteristics of Cubism and Futurism and is similar to the abstract work of Robert Delaunay, Francis Picabia, František Kupka, Léopold Survage, Piet Mondrian, and Hilma af Klint.",
     "section": "Context",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_VII#Context"
    }
   ],
