   "collection": "Musée National d'Art Moderne",
   "story": {
    "extract": "Auf Weiss II (Sur blanc II), in English: On White II, is a 1923 oil-on-canvas painting by Russian painter Wassily Kandinsky. It was created when the artist was a teacher at the Bauhaus in Weimar. The painting initially hung in the dining room of Wassily and Nina Kandinsky's apartment at Bauhaus Dessau.",
    "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auf_Weiss_II_%28Sur_blanc_II%29"
   },
   "facts": [
    {
     "text": "In this image, art historian Vanessa Morisset sees a whirlpool of centripetal forces emanating from its surface. The white, understood as clarity and simplicity, creates the feeling that the \"struggle with the canvas\" of Kandinsky had succeeded.",
     "section": "Reception",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auf_Weiss_II_%28Sur_blanc_II%29#Reception"
    },
    {
     "text": "The composition of the painting consists mainly of diagonals.",
     "section": "Description and analysis",
     "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auf_Weiss_II_%28Sur_blanc_II%29#Description_and_analysis"
    }
